{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cd1fb6d6-0063-4938-8f1f-f48812c8cc89","content":"## The Problem\n\n**.NET MAUI's Android workload bundles its own JDK** — the **Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17**. When your `JAVA_HOME` points to Adoptium Temurin, it overrides the bundled JDK and causes build failures because the Android build tooling (d8/r8/aapt2) expects the Microsoft distribution.\n\n## The Fix\n\n**Option 1 — Unset `JAVA_HOME`** so MAUI uses its bundled JDK:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build\n```\n\nTo make it permanent, remove the `JAVA_HOME` export from your `~/.zshrc` (or `~/.bash_profile`).\n\n**Option 2 — Point to the Microsoft OpenJDK** (installed by the workload):\n\n```bash\nexport JAVA_HOME=\"/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home\"\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Set it per-project** in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n> **TL;DR:** Don't override `JAVA_HOME` for MAUI builds — let the Android workload use its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5a009c74-41a3-4a4b-8508-a749f35cdf24","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what common issues exist with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java.\n\nThe most common issue here is that .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI uses JDK 17, but there can be issues with certain JDK distributions or versions.\n\nActually, the most likely issue is that .NET MAUI (especially .NET 8+) ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK distribution and expects to use that. The build system looks for the JDK in a specific location, and having a non-Microsoft JDK can cause issues.\n\n\nThe version itself shouldn't be the problem since they have JDK 17, but the real culprit is likely that the Android build tooling is configured to use Microsoft's OpenJDK specifically, while their JAVA_HOME or JavaSdkDirectory is pointing to the Adoptium distribution instead. On macOS especially, there's a known issue where the system picks up the wrong JDK installation.\n\nThe key insight is that .NET 8+ MAUI bundles its own Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17 with the Android workload, and when JAVA_HOME points elsewhere, it creates conflicts. The solution is usually to either unset JAVA_HOME entirely so the build system uses the bundled version, or explicitly point it to the Microsoft OpenJDK installation path. an external JDK like Adoptium Temurin can conflict with what the Android build tools expect. The fix is to either unset `JAVA_HOME` so MAUI uses its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17, or point it to the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK that comes with the MAUI workload—typically at `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home` on macOS. Alternatively, I can set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` directly in the `.csproj` file to override the default behavior.\n\nThe core issue is that the .NET Android SDK relies on its bundled JDK, and when `JAVA_HOME` points elsewhere, Android build steps like `aapt2`, `d8`, and `r8` fail because they were compiled against the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK. The cleanest solution is to let the SDK use its own JDK, or if other tools need `JAVA_HOME`, manage it per-project through MSBuild properties instead of setting it globally.","outputTokens":1482,"requestId":"9427:1DC2AE:14B6FC0:1720D87:6A0670CC"},"id":"8cda5aab-81f1-4a8b-b5b6-1849238103b5","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:03:36.864Z","parentId":"3b19dc63-054a-42cd-84cf-1435c0cd7ba4"}
